T1  - A two stage experimental design to test the efficiency of the market for traded stock options and the Australian evidence
AU  - Castagna, A.D.
AU  - Matolcsy, Z.P.
JO  - Journal of Banking & Finance
VL  - 6
IS  - 4
SP  - 521
EP  - 532
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/12/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/S0378-4266(82)80004-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0378426682800046
AB  - The aim of this paper is to develop a two stage experimental design to test the efficiency of the market for traded options. The experimental design does not require estimates of variance to be based on ex-post rates of returns, and assumes that all investors price options with the Black and Scholes model, adjusted for dividends. The first stage of the experiment derived estimates of ‘expected’ variance by `reversing' the Black and Scholes model. In the second stage of the experiment, the estimates of expected variance from stage one were used to generate daily option price series. Portfolios were subsequently developed from a number of trading strategies in order to generate indices of daily excess returns, which were tested for significance. Finally, transaction costs are considered to determine whether economic profits were available to option traders.
ER  - 

